> The combination of chicken and chickpeas in a rich tomato sauce gives this recipe a
> distinctly Iberian air. In Spain, this dish might be referred to as a Cocido, but
> here it's merely called delicious. For best results, serve hot with a side of
> freshly warmed baguette.

Preheat #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Peel and grate @garlic{2%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop
@parsley{5%g}(roughly chopped).

Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%pack}.

Quarter @mushrooms{150%g}. Chop larger pieces so all are evenly sized.

Pop @diced Irish chicken breast{260%g} into a large #oven dish{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and packaging.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due
> to vacuum packing used to keep it fresh.

Add @cherry tomatoes{125%g}, mushrooms, garlic, chickpeas, @paprika{2%sachets},
parsley and @dried chilli flakes{1%sachet} to the oven dish.

Carefully stir in the @passata{1%pack}, @water{100%ml}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and
@sugar{1/2%tsp}.

> Double all for 4p.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.
Toss to coat.

Bake until chicken is browned, about ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When 5 mins of cooking time remain, pop the @baguette{2} into the oven to warm
through, about ~{2-3%minutes}.

Serve up spoonfuls of hearty chicken and chickpea bake.

Pour over any juices from the oven dish.

Tear off chunks of warm baguette for mopping up the sauce.